      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/sqa-level2",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) are operated under documented software quality management systems. Ansys holds ISO 9001 certification; FDA and DePuy Synthes internal codes are version-controlled with formal release testing. Regression test suites covering linear elastic and nonlinear contact scenarios have been executed and passed. Gradation 3 achieved: formal SQA plans with documented test cases and traceability to requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ncv-level2",
      "rationale": "Code verification performed via comparison against analytic solutions for beam bending (Euler-Bernoulli and Timoshenko) and Hertzian contact. All three codes reproduce analytic solutions within 0.5% for the relevant load cases. Patch tests for mesh quality passed. Gradation 3 achieved: systematic code verification with documented results and quantified agreement metrics."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/de-level2",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence study conducted on the non-cannulated screw geometry using three refinement levels (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation applied to stiffness and peak von Mises stress QoIs. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the medium mesh: 1.3% for stiffness, 2.1% for peak stress. Medium mesh selected for production runs; discretization error contribution to total uncertainty budget is 2.1%. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nse-level1",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence monitored via force and displacement residuals; convergence tolerance set to 1×10⁻⁶ for all runs. No solver divergence or non-convergence events observed across the ensemble. Iterative solution error estimated at <0.1% of QoI values. Gradation 2 achieved: documented convergence criteria with quantified residuals."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ue-level2",
      "rationale": "Model setup reviewed independently by a second analyst at each participating organization. Boundary conditions, loading protocol, and material assignments were verified against the simulation plan prior to execution. A formal simulation plan with documented input parameters was approved before any production run. No discrepancies identified during cross-review. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/mf-level3",
      "rationale": "Continuum linear-elastic model with nonlinear contact (augmented Lagrange) used for screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. Model form justified by prior literature demonstrating that titanium alloy pedicle screws remain predominantly elastic under ASTM F1717 compression-bending loads up to yield. Plasticity model (isotropic hardening, Ramberg-Osgood) included for post-yield regime; calibrated against literature stress-strain data. Model form uncertainty assessed via comparison of elastic-only vs. elastic-plastic predictions; difference <3% for stiffness QoI, confirming model form is appropriate. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/mi-level3",
      "rationale": "Material properties for Ti-6Al-4V ELI sourced from peer-reviewed literature (ASTM F136, Boyer et al. 1994, Donachie 2000) in the absence of lot-specific coupon data. This gap is explicitly documented: elastic modulus E=114±14 GPa and yield strength σy=880±132 MPa (both ±2σ, 95% CI). Wide uncertainty bounds reflect genuine epistemic uncertainty from literature variability rather than measurement precision. Monte Carlo propagation (10,000 samples, Latin hypercube sampling) demonstrates that all three QoIs remain within the 10% acceptance threshold across the full uncertainty range, including the conservative lower-bound scenario. Geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of production screws (tolerance ±0.01 mm). Gradation 3 achieved with explicit documentation of the low-confidence material input gap and its bounded impact."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/ts-level3",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes R&D). Constructs assembled from production-representative components with documented lot traceability. Sample size justification: power analysis (α=0.05, β=0.2, effect size based on prior F1717 data) supports N≥8 for detecting a 10% mean difference; N=11 exceeds this threshold. Inter-laboratory variability characterized (CV 6–8% across QoIs); no statistically significant laboratory effect detected (two-sample t-test, p>0.05). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/tc-level2",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single test condition (ASTM F1717 standard protocol: quasi-static, room temperature, displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min, L5-S1 corpectomy model). The COU description acknowledges this limitation explicitly. Only one loading configuration (compression-bending) was applied; torsion and tension-bending conditions were not tested in this validation activity. Gradation 2 achieved (single standardized test condition). Required level 3 not met; this gap is carried as a documented limitation. The limitation is accepted because: (1) the COU is explicitly scoped to compression-bending only; (2) ASTM F1717 compression-bending is the primary regulatory submission test for this device class; (3) separate validation activities address torsion and tension-bending in companion COU packages."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/eip-level3",
      "rationale": "Simulation inputs mapped directly to experimental measurements: screw geometry from CMM data, rod geometry from caliper measurements, fixation block geometry from technical drawings. Material properties assigned consistently between simulation and test article specification (Ti-6Al-4V ELI per ASTM F136). Boundary conditions replicate test fixture constraints: fixed base block, axial load applied at superior block centroid, lateral offset per ASTM F1717 Table 1. Equivalency confirmed by independent review; no uncontrolled differences identified. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/oc-level3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using both percentage difference (acceptance criterion <10%) and validation metric E/uval (acceptance criterion <1.96). Results: stiffness 1.9%/0.61, yield force 2.4%/0.83, force at 40 mm 1.7%/0.54. All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria with substantial margin. Uncertainty in experimental mean (SEM, 95% CI) and simulation uncertainty (material property propagation, discretization error, solver error) combined in quadrature for E/uval calculation per ASME V&V 20. Gradation 4 achieved: multiple QoIs, multiple acceptance metrics, full uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rqi-level3",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs selected — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly relevant to the clinical COU. Construct stiffness governs load sharing and adjacent segment effects; yield force indicates onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield structural integrity relevant to revision surgery trigger thresholds. All three QoIs are extractable from both simulation output and experimental data acquisition systems without post-processing assumptions. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/rvac-level3",
      "rationale": "Validation activity directly replicates the COU: same device geometry (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw), same test standard (ASTM F1717), same loading mode (compression-bending), same regulatory context (Class II 510(k) submission). The validation model and the predictive model are the same FEA ensemble; no extrapolation across geometry, material, or loading regime is required. The single test condition gap (Gradation 2 for Test conditions) does not undermine relevance because the COU is explicitly scoped to compression-bending. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
